{"title_page": "Lejla Basic", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Lejla Basic|timestamp=20200323205532|year=2020|month=March|day=23|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Lejla Basic|date=23 March 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|Swedish football midfielder|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Lejla Basic\n| fullname    = Lejla Basic\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1994|10|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Sweden]]\n| height      = \n| position    = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF|KIF Orebro]]\n| clubnumber  = 19\n| years1 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs1 = [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF|KIF Orebro]]\n| caps1  = 11\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs2 = [[\u00c4lta IF|Alta]]\n| caps2  = 32\n| goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF|KIF Orebro]]\n| caps3  = 41\n| goals3 = 3\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\n| nationalteam1 = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina women's national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 09:35, 21 May 2016 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Lejla Basic''' (born 3 October 1994) is a Swedish [[Association football|football]] midfielder who plays for [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF]].\n\n==Career==\nBasic began her career with [[KIF Orebro DFF|KIF \u00d6rebro]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Sveriges Radio]]|title=Kif f\u00f6rl\u00e4nger med Lejla Basic|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=159&artikel=6561157|language=sv|date=11 November 2016|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> She helped lead the club to promotion during the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[\u00d6stersunds-Posten]]|title=Mittf\u00e4ltaren har blommat ut under nya tr\u00e4naren: \"Jag har f\u00e5tt ett stort f\u00f6rtroende\"|url=https://www.op.se/logga-in/mittfaltaren-har-blommat-ut-under-nya-tranaren-jag-har-fatt-ett-stort-fortroende|language=sv|date=20 June 2018|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBasic made one appearance for the [[Bosnia and Herzegovina women's national football team]], a 1\u20132 defeat to Croatia in a friendly on 9 June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfsbih.ba/vijesti/bh-seniorke-u-drugom-mecu-izgubile-od-hrvatske/|title=Bh seniorke u drugom me\u010du izgubile od Hrvatske|website=www.nfsbih.ba}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Soccerway|lejla-basic/293630}}\n\n{{KIF \u00d6rebro DFF squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basic, Lejla}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:KIF \u00d6rebro DFF players]]\n[[Category:Damallsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina women's international footballers]]\n\n{{Sweden-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n{{Sweden-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Lejla Basic|timestamp=20200323205532|year=2020|month=March|day=23|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Lejla Basic|date=23 March 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|Swedish football midfielder|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Lejla Basic\n| fullname    = Lejla Basic\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1994|10|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Sweden]]\n| height      = \n| position    = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF|KIF Orebro]]\n| clubnumber  = 19\n| years1 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs1 = [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF|KIF Orebro]]\n| caps1  = 11\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs2 = [[\u00c4lta IF|Alta]]\n| caps2  = 32\n| goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF|KIF Orebro]]\n| caps3  = 41\n| goals3 = 3\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\n| nationalteam1 = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina women's national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 09:35, 21 May 2016 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Lejla Basic''' (born 3 October 1994) is a Swedish [[Association football|football]] midfielder who plays for [[KIF \u00d6rebro DFF]].\n\n==Career==\nBasic began her career with [[KIF Orebro DFF|KIF \u00d6rebro]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Sveriges Radio]]|title=Kif f\u00f6rl\u00e4nger med Lejla Basic|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=159&artikel=6561157|language=sv|date=11 November 2016|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> She helped lead the club to promotion during the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[\u00d6stersunds-Posten]]|title=Mittf\u00e4ltaren har blommat ut under nya tr\u00e4naren: \"Jag har f\u00e5tt ett stort f\u00f6rtroende\"|url=https://www.op.se/logga-in/mittfaltaren-har-blommat-ut-under-nya-tranaren-jag-har-fatt-ett-stort-fortroende|language=sv|date=20 June 2018|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBasic made one appearance for the [[Bosnia and Herzegovina women's national football team]], a 1\u20132 defeat to Croatia in a friendly on 9 June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfsbih.ba/vijesti/bh-seniorke-u-drugom-mecu-izgubile-od-hrvatske/|title=Bh seniorke u drugom me\u010du izgubile od Hrvatske|website=www.nfsbih.ba}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Soccerway|lejla-basic/293630}}\n\n{{KIF \u00d6rebro DFF squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basic, Lejla}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:KIF \u00d6rebro DFF players]]\n[[Category:Damallsvenskan players]]\n\n{{Sweden-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n{{Sweden-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lejla_Basic"}
{"title_page": "Alexandria Villase\u00f1or", "text_new": "{{short description|American climate activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Alexandria Villase\u00f1or\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|2005|5|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Davis, California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[European-American]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Student<br />Environmental activist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[School strike for climate]]\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Alexandria Villase\u00f1or''' (born 18 May 2005) is a [[European Americans|European-American]] [[climate activist]] living in [[New York City]]. A follower of the [[School strike for climate|Fridays for Future movement]] and of fellow climate activist [[Greta Thunberg]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/how-a-7th-graders-strike-against-climate-change-exploded-into-a-movement/2019/02/15/e20868e2-2fb4-11e9-86ab-5d02109aeb01_story.html?noredirect=on |title=How a 7th-grader's strike against climate change exploded into a movement |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Sarah |last=Kaplan |date=16 February 2019 |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref> Villase\u00f1or is a co-founder of US Youth Climate Strike and founder of Earth Uprising.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://thebulletin.org/biography/alexandria-villasenor/ |title= Alexandria Villase\u00f1or |website= Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists| accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nVillase\u00f1or was born in 2005 in [[Davis, California]], where she grew up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Milman |first1=Oliver |title='We won't stop striking': the New York 13 year-old taking a stand over climate change |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/mar/12/climate-change-student-activists-environment |accessdate=20 July 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kaplan WP\">{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/how-a-7th-graders-strike-against-climate-change-exploded-into-a-movement/2019/02/15/e20868e2-2fb4-11e9-86ab-5d02109aeb01_story.html |title=How a 7th-grader's strike against climate change exploded into a movement | work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=4 May 2019 | first=Sarah |last=Kaplan |date=16 February 2019}}</ref> The family moved from [[northern California]] to New York City during 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Piven |first1=Ben |title=Beware the kids: US youth to join strike for climate |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/beware-kids-youth-join-strike-climate-190314052008643.html |accessdate=8 May 2019 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=15 March 2019}}</ref> Villase\u00f1or is Latina.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://glittermagrocks.com/connect/2019/06/24/meet-alexandria-villasenor-the-young-woman-inspiring-people-to-take-action-on-the-climate-change-crisis/ |title=Meet Alexandria Villase\u00f1or, the Young Woman Inspiring People to Take Action on the Climate Change Crisis |date=24 June 2019|website=Glitter Magazine |access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref> Her goal is to one day work for the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minutaglio |first1=Rose |title=The World Is Burning. These Girls Are Fighting to Save It. |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/a26755814/youth-climate-strike-march-15/ |accessdate=20 July 2019 |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nVillase\u00f1or's fight for climate action was sparked when she was caught in a smoke cloud from the November 2018 [[Camp Fire (2018)|Camp Fire]] in [[California]] during a family visit. As an [[asthma]] sufferer, she became physically ill, during which time she researched the [[climate change]] and temperature rises which contributed to the fire's severity.<ref name=\"Kaplan WP\" /> Her mother was enrolled for climate change courses at [[Columbia University]] and she sat in on those, learning about the underlying science.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Borunda |first1=Alejandra |title=These young activists are striking to save their planet from climate change |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2019/03/youth-climate-strike-kids-save-the-world/ |accessdate=20 July 2019 |work=[[National Geographic]] |date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Soon afterward, she joined New York's chapter of Zero Hour, a group of American youth climate activists.<ref name=\"Kaplan WP\" />\n\nVillase\u00f1or has taken similar climate action to Thunberg, who inspired her with her 4 December 2018 talk at the [[2018 United Nations Climate Change Conference|United Nations Climate Change Conference]] (COP24) in [[Katowice]], Poland. Since 14 December 2018 (while COP24 was still held),<ref name=\"Kaplan WP\" /> she skips school every Friday in order to protest against lack of climate action in front of the [[Headquarters of the United Nations]] in New York.<ref>{{cite news | first1=Jeff |last1=Berardelli |first2=Haley |last2=Ott |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/greta-thunberg-alexandria-villasenor-teens-leading-global-movement-ditch-school-fight-climate-change/ |title= Meet the teens leading a global movement to ditch school and fight climate change |work= [[CBS News]] |accessdate=4 May 2019 |date=22 February 2019}}</ref> She is no longer involved with the US Youth Climate Strike group<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Co Executive Directors & National Co-Directors |url= https://www.youthclimatestrikeus.org/about |publisher=US Youth Climate Strike |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> and founded the climate change education group Earth Uprising.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stuart |first1=Tessa |title=A New Generation of Activists Is Taking the Lead on Climate Change |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/climate-change-school-strike-825719/ |accessdate=8 May 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Villase\u00f1or was the recipient of the Disruptor Award from the Tribeca Disruptive Innovation Awards (TDIA),<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Tribeca Film Festival and Disruptor Foundation announce 10th anniversary awards and youngest recipient in TDIA history |url= https://www.disruptorawards.com/press-release?rq=alexandria |location=New York |publisher=Disruptor Foundation |agency= |date=2 April 2019 |access-date=8 May 2019}}</ref> received a scholarship from The Common Good public advocacy organization,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Common Good Forum & American Spirit Awards \u2013 May 10, 2019 |url= https://www.thecommongoodus.org/2019/05/the-common-good-forum-american-spirit-awards-friday-may-10-2019/ |publisher=The Common Good |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alexandria Villase\u00f1or |url= https://www.thecommongoodus.org/2019/05/alexandria-villasenor/ |publisher=The Common Good |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref> and was awarded a Youth Climate Leadership prize from [[Earth Day Network]].<ref>{{cite web |title=14-Year-Old Alexandria Villase\u00f1or Has Been Striking Outside UN Headquarters for 5 Months. Here\u2019s Why |url=https://www.earthday.org/2019/05/23/14-year-old-alexandria-villasenor-has-been-striking-outside-un-headquarters-for-5-months-heres-why/ |publisher=[[Earth Day Network]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhen Thunberg arrived to New York City from her [[Voyage of Greta Thunberg|transatlantic sailboat voyage]] in August 2019, Villase\u00f1or, [[Xiye Bastida]], and other climate activists greeted Thunberg upon arrival.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/kidspost/greta-thunbergs-us-visit-inspires-young-climate-activists/2019/09/09/91a422f6-ce88-11e9-87fa-8501a456c003_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Greta Thunberg\u2019s New York visit inspires young climate activists|newspaper=Washington Post|language=English|author=Lela Nargi|date=9 September 2019|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> By that time, they had already established contact with each other over [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/klimat/14-ariga-klimataktivisten-om-vanskapen-med-greta/|title=14-\u00e5riga klimataktivisten Alexandria Villase\u00f1or om v\u00e4nskapen med Greta Thunberg|newspaper=Expressen|language=English|author=Lela Nargi|date=22 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn 23 September 2019, Villase\u00f1or, along with 15 other youth activists including [[Greta Thunberg]], [[Catarina Lorenzo]], and [[Carl Smith (climate activist)|Carl Smith]], filed a legal complaint with the [[United Nations]] accusing five countries, namely [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Brazil]], [[Argentina]], and [[Turkey]] of failing to uphold their reduction targets to which they committed in their [[Paris Agreement]] pledges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earther.gizmodo.com/why-teen-climate-activist-alexandria-villasenor-is-suin-1838370232|title=Why Teen Climate Activist Alexandria Villase\u00f1or Is Suing the World For Violating Her Rights|website=Earther|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/16-children-including-greta-thunberg-file-landmark-complaint-united-nations|title=16 children, including Greta Thunberg, file landmark complaint to the United Nations Committee on the Rights of the Child|website=www.unicef.org|language=en|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-October 2019, she attended the [[C40 World Mayors Summit]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://c40summit2019.org/newsroom/announcements/|title=Press Conferences|publisher=C40 World Mayors Summit|language=English|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Twitter | id= alexandriav2005 | name= Alexandria Villase\u00f1or }}\n* {{Instagram | id= alexandriav2005 | name= Alexandria Villase\u00f1or }}\n{{School strike for climate}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Villasenor, Alexandria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2005 births]]\n[[Category:Climate change environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Youth activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:Climate activists]]\n[[Category:American child activists]]\n[[Category:American women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American climate activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Alexandria Villase\u00f1or\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|2005|5|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Davis, California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Student<br />Environmental activist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = [[School strike for climate]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Alexandria Villase\u00f1or''' (born 18 May 2005) is an American [[climate activist]] living in [[New York City]]. A follower of the [[School strike for climate|Fridays for Future movement]] and of fellow climate activist [[Greta Thunberg]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/how-a-7th-graders-strike-against-climate-change-exploded-into-a-movement/2019/02/15/e20868e2-2fb4-11e9-86ab-5d02109aeb01_story.html?noredirect=on |title=How a 7th-grader's strike against climate change exploded into a movement |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Sarah |last=Kaplan |date=16 February 2019 |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref> Villase\u00f1or is a co-founder of US Youth Climate Strike and founder of Earth Uprising.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://thebulletin.org/biography/alexandria-villasenor/ |title= Alexandria Villase\u00f1or |website= Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists| accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nVillase\u00f1or was born in 2005 in [[Davis, California]], where she grew up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Milman |first1=Oliver |title='We won't stop striking': the New York 13 year-old taking a stand over climate change |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/mar/12/climate-change-student-activists-environment |accessdate=20 July 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kaplan WP\">{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/how-a-7th-graders-strike-against-climate-change-exploded-into-a-movement/2019/02/15/e20868e2-2fb4-11e9-86ab-5d02109aeb01_story.html |title=How a 7th-grader's strike against climate change exploded into a movement | work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=4 May 2019 | first=Sarah |last=Kaplan |date=16 February 2019}}</ref> The family moved from [[northern California]] to New York City during 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Piven |first1=Ben |title=Beware the kids: US youth to join strike for climate |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/beware-kids-youth-join-strike-climate-190314052008643.html |accessdate=8 May 2019 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=15 March 2019}}</ref> Villase\u00f1or is Latina.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://glittermagrocks.com/connect/2019/06/24/meet-alexandria-villasenor-the-young-woman-inspiring-people-to-take-action-on-the-climate-change-crisis/ |title=Meet Alexandria Villase\u00f1or, the Young Woman Inspiring People to Take Action on the Climate Change Crisis |date=24 June 2019|website=Glitter Magazine |access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref> Her goal is to one day work for the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minutaglio |first1=Rose |title=The World Is Burning. These Girls Are Fighting to Save It. |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/a26755814/youth-climate-strike-march-15/ |accessdate=20 July 2019 |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nVillase\u00f1or's fight for climate action was sparked when she was caught in a smoke cloud from the November 2018 [[Camp Fire (2018)|Camp Fire]] in [[California]] during a family visit. As an [[asthma]] sufferer, she became physically ill, during which time she researched the [[climate change]] and temperature rises which contributed to the fire's severity.<ref name=\"Kaplan WP\" /> Her mother was enrolled for climate change courses at [[Columbia University]] and she sat in on those, learning about the underlying science.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Borunda |first1=Alejandra |title=These young activists are striking to save their planet from climate change |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2019/03/youth-climate-strike-kids-save-the-world/ |accessdate=20 July 2019 |work=[[National Geographic]] |date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Soon afterward, she joined New York's chapter of Zero Hour, a group of American youth climate activists.<ref name=\"Kaplan WP\" />\n\nVillase\u00f1or has taken similar climate action to Thunberg, who inspired her with her 4 December 2018 talk at the [[2018 United Nations Climate Change Conference|United Nations Climate Change Conference]] (COP24) in [[Katowice]], Poland. Since 14 December 2018 (while COP24 was still held),<ref name=\"Kaplan WP\" /> she skips school every Friday in order to protest against lack of climate action in front of the [[Headquarters of the United Nations]] in New York.<ref>{{cite news | first1=Jeff |last1=Berardelli |first2=Haley |last2=Ott |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/greta-thunberg-alexandria-villasenor-teens-leading-global-movement-ditch-school-fight-climate-change/ |title= Meet the teens leading a global movement to ditch school and fight climate change |work= [[CBS News]] |accessdate=4 May 2019 |date=22 February 2019}}</ref> She is no longer involved with the US Youth Climate Strike group<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Co Executive Directors & National Co-Directors |url= https://www.youthclimatestrikeus.org/about |publisher=US Youth Climate Strike |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> and founded the climate change education group Earth Uprising.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stuart |first1=Tessa |title=A New Generation of Activists Is Taking the Lead on Climate Change |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/climate-change-school-strike-825719/ |accessdate=8 May 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Villase\u00f1or was the recipient of the Disruptor Award from the Tribeca Disruptive Innovation Awards (TDIA),<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Tribeca Film Festival and Disruptor Foundation announce 10th anniversary awards and youngest recipient in TDIA history |url= https://www.disruptorawards.com/press-release?rq=alexandria |location=New York |publisher=Disruptor Foundation |agency= |date=2 April 2019 |access-date=8 May 2019}}</ref> received a scholarship from The Common Good public advocacy organization,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Common Good Forum & American Spirit Awards \u2013 May 10, 2019 |url= https://www.thecommongoodus.org/2019/05/the-common-good-forum-american-spirit-awards-friday-may-10-2019/ |publisher=The Common Good |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alexandria Villase\u00f1or |url= https://www.thecommongoodus.org/2019/05/alexandria-villasenor/ |publisher=The Common Good |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref> and was awarded a Youth Climate Leadership prize from [[Earth Day Network]].<ref>{{cite web |title=14-Year-Old Alexandria Villase\u00f1or Has Been Striking Outside UN Headquarters for 5 Months. Here\u2019s Why |url=https://www.earthday.org/2019/05/23/14-year-old-alexandria-villasenor-has-been-striking-outside-un-headquarters-for-5-months-heres-why/ |publisher=[[Earth Day Network]] |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhen Thunberg arrived to New York City from her [[Voyage of Greta Thunberg|transatlantic sailboat voyage]] in August 2019, Villase\u00f1or, [[Xiye Bastida]], and other climate activists greeted Thunberg upon arrival.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/kidspost/greta-thunbergs-us-visit-inspires-young-climate-activists/2019/09/09/91a422f6-ce88-11e9-87fa-8501a456c003_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Greta Thunberg\u2019s New York visit inspires young climate activists|newspaper=Washington Post|language=English|author=Lela Nargi|date=9 September 2019|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> By that time, they had already established contact with each other over [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/klimat/14-ariga-klimataktivisten-om-vanskapen-med-greta/|title=14-\u00e5riga klimataktivisten Alexandria Villase\u00f1or om v\u00e4nskapen med Greta Thunberg|newspaper=Expressen|language=English|author=Lela Nargi|date=22 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn 23 September 2019, Villase\u00f1or, along with 15 other youth activists including [[Greta Thunberg]], [[Catarina Lorenzo]], and [[Carl Smith (climate activist)|Carl Smith]], filed a legal complaint with the [[United Nations]] accusing five countries, namely [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Brazil]], [[Argentina]], and [[Turkey]] of failing to uphold their reduction targets to which they committed in their [[Paris Agreement]] pledges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earther.gizmodo.com/why-teen-climate-activist-alexandria-villasenor-is-suin-1838370232|title=Why Teen Climate Activist Alexandria Villase\u00f1or Is Suing the World For Violating Her Rights|website=Earther|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/16-children-including-greta-thunberg-file-landmark-complaint-united-nations|title=16 children, including Greta Thunberg, file landmark complaint to the United Nations Committee on the Rights of the Child|website=www.unicef.org|language=en|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-October 2019, she attended the [[C40 World Mayors Summit]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://c40summit2019.org/newsroom/announcements/|title=Press Conferences|publisher=C40 World Mayors Summit|language=English|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Twitter | id= alexandriav2005 | name= Alexandria Villase\u00f1or }}\n* {{Instagram | id= alexandriav2005 | name= Alexandria Villase\u00f1or }}\n{{School strike for climate}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Villasenor, Alexandria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2005 births]]\n[[Category:Climate change environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Youth activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:Climate activists]]\n[[Category:American child activists]]\n[[Category:American women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n", "name_user": "Gildsons", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandria_Villase%C3%B1or"}
{"title_page": "Katie Eder", "text_new": "{{short description|American activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Katie Eder\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_place        = [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| nationality        = [[European-American]]\n| known_for          = Founder [[50 Miles More]]\n}}\n'''Katie Eder''' is an activist and social entrepreneur who founded and has led three social impact ventures: [[50MilesMore|50 Miles More]], Kids Tales, and [[Future Coalition|The Future Coalition]] where she is currently the Executive Director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spirit.prudential.com/honoree/2018/wi/sarah-katie-eder|title=The Prudential Spirit Of Community Awards|website=spirit.prudential.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/05/students-will-leave-classes-on-tuesday-as-part-of-the-walkout-to-vote.html|title=Students will leave classes on Tuesday as part of the Walkout to Vote|last=Hess|first=Abigail|date=2018-11-06|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/sudents-walking-out-of-classes-today-to-vote-at-the-polls-2018-11|title=Thousands of American students are walking out of classes today and heading to the polls to vote|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|date=2018-11-07|website=Business Insider Australia|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Eder was named one of [[Forbes 30 under 30]] in Law and Policy.<ref>https://www.forbes.com/pictures/5ddd7cb0ea103f0006537307/katie-eder-20/#212e4b757fc7</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nKatie Eder was born and raised in Milwaukee, Wisconsin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wuwm.com/post/wisconsin-students-take-protest-house-speakers-backyard|title=Wisconsin Students Take Protest To House Speaker&#039;s Backyard|last=Teich|first=Teran Powell, Joy Powers, Mitch|website=www.wuwm.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> Katie graduated from Shorewood High School in 2018 and will attend [[Stanford University]] in the fall of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amysmartgirls.com/katie-eder-on-helping-kids-and-teens-find-their-voices-through-writing-and-marching-ea4e0bf812bf|title=Katie Eder on Helping Kids and Teens Find Their Voices Through Writing and Marching|last=Mason|first=Heather|date=2018-08-28|website=Amy Poehler's Smart Girls|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> She is the youngest of five children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishchronicle.org/2015/08/30/shorewood-teen-helps-children-tell-their-unique-stories/|title=Shorewood teen helps children tell their unique stories {{!}} Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|website=www.jewishchronicle.org|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\n\n=== Kids Tales ===\nWhen Katie was 13 years old, she founded a nonprofit organization, Kids Tales, to bring creative writing workshops, taught by teens, to kids who do not have access to writing experiences outside of school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spirit.prudential.com/honoree/2018/wi/sarah-katie-eder|title=The Prudential Spirit Of Community Awards|website=spirit.prudential.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/education/2017/08/25/wisconsin-teens-creative-writing-program-kids-tales-has-global-reach/591035001/|title=Wisconsin teen's creative writing program Kids Tales has global reach|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> During a Kids Tales workshop, kids write a short story that is published in an anthology, a real book.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ysa.org/eyh-katie-eder/|website=ysa.org|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.literacyworldwide.org/blog/literacy-daily/2016/01/28/teen-takes-writing-inspiration-to-fellow-students|title=Teen Takes Writing Inspiration to Fellow Students|website=www.literacyworldwide.org|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> Fifteen hundred kids in nine countries have participated in Kids Tales workshops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.entrepreneurbefore25.com/episodes/102-changing-the-world-while-still-in-high-school-with-katie-eder/|title=102: Changing the world while still in high school with Katie Eder|website=Entrepreneur Before 25|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/milwaukee/news/2015/09/01/global-literacy-organization-honors-kids-tales.html|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> Kids Tales has engaged over 400 teen teachers and published 90 anthologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://radio.thepeacefund.org/heroes/katie-eder|title=Katie Eder - PEACE Fund Radio Hero of the Week|website=The PEACE Fund|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://untitledtown2018.sched.com/list/descriptions/|title=UntitledTown Book and Author Festival Schedule|website=untitledtown2018.sched.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n=== 50 Miles More ===\nAfter the 2018 March For Our Lives events ended on March 24, Katie and other students from her high school organized a 50 mile march from Madison, WI to Janesville, WI, the hometown of former U.S. Speaker of the House Paul Ryan, to call him out for his role in blocking and burying gun legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yr.media/news/why-this-wisconsin-teen-is-marching-50-miles-to-protest-gun-violence/|title=Why This Wisconsin Teen Is Marching 50 Miles to Protest Gun Violence|date=2018-03-27|website=YR Media|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2018/03/25/50-miles-more-march-for-our-lives-paul-ryan/|title=Wisconsin high school students to walk 50 miles, dare Paul Ryan not to act on gun reform|last=Ruiz|first=Rebecca|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> This 50 Miles More march lead Katie and her team to launch a nationwide campaign called #50more in #50states to challenge the other 49 states to hold 50 Mile Marches to the hometown or office of one of their NRA-backed elected officials to demand they take action to end gun violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2018/03/194639/march-for-our-lives-50-miles-more-wisconsin|title=These Wisconsin High Schoolers Are Marching 50 Miles For Gun Control \u2014 To Paul Ryan's Hometown|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/students-take-50-mile-march-paul-ryans-hometown-continue-march-our-lives-860846|title=Students trek 50 miles to Paul Ryan's hometown to continue March For Our Lives|last=PM|first=Tracy Lee On 3/26/18 at 6:26|date=2018-03-26|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> 50 Miles More did 50 mile walk in Massachusetts in August 2018. 50 Miles More also innovated a nationwide youth-led voter engagement initiative targeting these newly engaged marchers to get them to the polls to vote in the 2018 midterm elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2018/03/27/wisconsin-students-marching-50-miles-paul-ryans-hometown-action-gun-laws/461407002/|title=Wisconsin students are marching 50 miles to Paul Ryan's hometown for action on gun laws|last=Seyler|first=Lainy|date=March 27, 2018|website=USA Today|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/25/politics/march-for-our-lives-wisconsin-activism-gun-reform-paul-ryan/index.html|title=In Wisconsin, they're not done marching. Next stop: Paul Ryan's hometown|last=Hamedy|first=Saba|date=March 26, 2018|website=CNN.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Future Coalition ===\nKatie led 50 Miles More to forge alliances with other youth-led organizations across the country to form the Future Coalition, a national network and community for young people and youth-led organizations with the goal of making the future a better, safer, and more just place for everyone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/sudents-walking-out-of-classes-today-to-vote-at-the-polls-2018-11|title=Thousands of students are walking out of classes today and heading to the polls to vote|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|website=INSIDER|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/young-voters-march-shout-walk-vote-181106125006538.html|title=Young voters: We can march, shout and walk out, but we must vote {{!}} USA News {{!}} Al Jazeera|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> The Future Coalition connects youth-led organizations and youth leaders across the United States to share resources and ideas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/student-walk-outs-vote-polls-2018-midterm-elections-825a0c2f-2d02-42ae-9ec4-759f7d965986.html|title=Students across the U.S. plan walk-outs to vote in midterm elections|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/what-is-the-walkout-to-vote-young-people-are-taking-their-power-to-the-polls-13092205|title=This Teen Activist Is Giving You One Good Reason Why You Should Get Out & Vote|last=Golden|first=Hannah|website=Elite Daily|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> The Future Coalition launched in September 2018 with the election campaign Walkout to Vote. Over 500 schools across the country walked out of class and marched to the polls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/377923-wisconsin-students-to-march-50-miles-to-ryans-hometown-to|title=Students to march 50 miles to Ryan's hometown to demand gun control|last=Savransky|first=Rebecca|date=2018-03-12|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowthisnews.com/https://nowthisnews.com/videos/politics/wisconsin-students-are-marching-to-paul-ryans-hometown|title=Wisconsin Students Are Marching To Paul Ryan's Hometown|last=nowthisnews|date=2018-03-29|website=NowThis|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards ==\n\n* Prudential Spirit of Community Award \u2013 National Honoree<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spirit.prudential.com/honoree/2018/wi/sarah-katie-eder|title=The Prudential Spirit Of Community Awards|website=spirit.prudential.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n* Diller Tikkun Olam Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dillerteenawards.org/recipient/sarah-katherine-eder/|title=Award for Jewish Teen Leaders - Diller Teen Tikkun Olam Awards|website=www.dillerteenawards.org|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n* Three Dot Dash \u2013 Global Social Entrepreneurship Incubator \u2013 Just Peace Summit<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.threedotdash.org/2017mentorgoals/|title=2017 GTL Goals & Expectations MENTOR|website=three dot dash|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n* International Literacy Association \u2013 30 under 30 Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.literacyworldwide.org/docs/default-source/communications/literacy-today/lt-30-under-30-2015.pdf|website=www.literacyworldwide.org|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n* AFS-USA Project Change \u2013 Vision in Action Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afsusa.org/returnees/blog/article?article_id=8502|title=Returnee Spotlight on: Sam Harshbarger and Katie Eder|website=Blog|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<references group=\"\"></references>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eder, Katie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Organization founders]]\n[[Category:American gun control activists]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Youth activists]]\n[[Category:American child activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Katie Eder\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_place        = [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| known_for          = Founder [[50 Miles More]]\n}}\n'''Katie Eder''' is an activist and social entrepreneur who founded and has led three social impact ventures: [[50MilesMore|50 Miles More]], Kids Tales, and [[Future Coalition|The Future Coalition]] where she is currently the Executive Director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spirit.prudential.com/honoree/2018/wi/sarah-katie-eder|title=The Prudential Spirit Of Community Awards|website=spirit.prudential.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/05/students-will-leave-classes-on-tuesday-as-part-of-the-walkout-to-vote.html|title=Students will leave classes on Tuesday as part of the Walkout to Vote|last=Hess|first=Abigail|date=2018-11-06|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/sudents-walking-out-of-classes-today-to-vote-at-the-polls-2018-11|title=Thousands of American students are walking out of classes today and heading to the polls to vote|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|date=2018-11-07|website=Business Insider Australia|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Eder was named one of [[Forbes 30 under 30]] in Law and Policy.<ref>https://www.forbes.com/pictures/5ddd7cb0ea103f0006537307/katie-eder-20/#212e4b757fc7</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nKatie Eder was born and raised in Milwaukee, Wisconsin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wuwm.com/post/wisconsin-students-take-protest-house-speakers-backyard|title=Wisconsin Students Take Protest To House Speaker&#039;s Backyard|last=Teich|first=Teran Powell, Joy Powers, Mitch|website=www.wuwm.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> Katie graduated from Shorewood High School in 2018 and will attend [[Stanford University]] in the fall of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amysmartgirls.com/katie-eder-on-helping-kids-and-teens-find-their-voices-through-writing-and-marching-ea4e0bf812bf|title=Katie Eder on Helping Kids and Teens Find Their Voices Through Writing and Marching|last=Mason|first=Heather|date=2018-08-28|website=Amy Poehler's Smart Girls|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> She is the youngest of five children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishchronicle.org/2015/08/30/shorewood-teen-helps-children-tell-their-unique-stories/|title=Shorewood teen helps children tell their unique stories {{!}} Wisconsin Jewish Chronicle|website=www.jewishchronicle.org|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\n\n=== Kids Tales ===\nWhen Katie was 13 years old, she founded a nonprofit organization, Kids Tales, to bring creative writing workshops, taught by teens, to kids who do not have access to writing experiences outside of school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spirit.prudential.com/honoree/2018/wi/sarah-katie-eder|title=The Prudential Spirit Of Community Awards|website=spirit.prudential.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/education/2017/08/25/wisconsin-teens-creative-writing-program-kids-tales-has-global-reach/591035001/|title=Wisconsin teen's creative writing program Kids Tales has global reach|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> During a Kids Tales workshop, kids write a short story that is published in an anthology, a real book.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ysa.org/eyh-katie-eder/|website=ysa.org|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.literacyworldwide.org/blog/literacy-daily/2016/01/28/teen-takes-writing-inspiration-to-fellow-students|title=Teen Takes Writing Inspiration to Fellow Students|website=www.literacyworldwide.org|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> Fifteen hundred kids in nine countries have participated in Kids Tales workshops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.entrepreneurbefore25.com/episodes/102-changing-the-world-while-still-in-high-school-with-katie-eder/|title=102: Changing the world while still in high school with Katie Eder|website=Entrepreneur Before 25|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/milwaukee/news/2015/09/01/global-literacy-organization-honors-kids-tales.html|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> Kids Tales has engaged over 400 teen teachers and published 90 anthologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://radio.thepeacefund.org/heroes/katie-eder|title=Katie Eder - PEACE Fund Radio Hero of the Week|website=The PEACE Fund|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://untitledtown2018.sched.com/list/descriptions/|title=UntitledTown Book and Author Festival Schedule|website=untitledtown2018.sched.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n=== 50 Miles More ===\nAfter the 2018 March For Our Lives events ended on March 24, Katie and other students from her high school organized a 50 mile march from Madison, WI to Janesville, WI, the hometown of former U.S. Speaker of the House Paul Ryan, to call him out for his role in blocking and burying gun legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yr.media/news/why-this-wisconsin-teen-is-marching-50-miles-to-protest-gun-violence/|title=Why This Wisconsin Teen Is Marching 50 Miles to Protest Gun Violence|date=2018-03-27|website=YR Media|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2018/03/25/50-miles-more-march-for-our-lives-paul-ryan/|title=Wisconsin high school students to walk 50 miles, dare Paul Ryan not to act on gun reform|last=Ruiz|first=Rebecca|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> This 50 Miles More march lead Katie and her team to launch a nationwide campaign called #50more in #50states to challenge the other 49 states to hold 50 Mile Marches to the hometown or office of one of their NRA-backed elected officials to demand they take action to end gun violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2018/03/194639/march-for-our-lives-50-miles-more-wisconsin|title=These Wisconsin High Schoolers Are Marching 50 Miles For Gun Control \u2014 To Paul Ryan's Hometown|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/students-take-50-mile-march-paul-ryans-hometown-continue-march-our-lives-860846|title=Students trek 50 miles to Paul Ryan's hometown to continue March For Our Lives|last=PM|first=Tracy Lee On 3/26/18 at 6:26|date=2018-03-26|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> 50 Miles More did 50 mile walk in Massachusetts in August 2018. 50 Miles More also innovated a nationwide youth-led voter engagement initiative targeting these newly engaged marchers to get them to the polls to vote in the 2018 midterm elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2018/03/27/wisconsin-students-marching-50-miles-paul-ryans-hometown-action-gun-laws/461407002/|title=Wisconsin students are marching 50 miles to Paul Ryan's hometown for action on gun laws|last=Seyler|first=Lainy|date=March 27, 2018|website=USA Today|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/25/politics/march-for-our-lives-wisconsin-activism-gun-reform-paul-ryan/index.html|title=In Wisconsin, they're not done marching. Next stop: Paul Ryan's hometown|last=Hamedy|first=Saba|date=March 26, 2018|website=CNN.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Future Coalition ===\nKatie led 50 Miles More to forge alliances with other youth-led organizations across the country to form the Future Coalition, a national network and community for young people and youth-led organizations with the goal of making the future a better, safer, and more just place for everyone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/sudents-walking-out-of-classes-today-to-vote-at-the-polls-2018-11|title=Thousands of students are walking out of classes today and heading to the polls to vote|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|website=INSIDER|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/young-voters-march-shout-walk-vote-181106125006538.html|title=Young voters: We can march, shout and walk out, but we must vote {{!}} USA News {{!}} Al Jazeera|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> The Future Coalition connects youth-led organizations and youth leaders across the United States to share resources and ideas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/student-walk-outs-vote-polls-2018-midterm-elections-825a0c2f-2d02-42ae-9ec4-759f7d965986.html|title=Students across the U.S. plan walk-outs to vote in midterm elections|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/what-is-the-walkout-to-vote-young-people-are-taking-their-power-to-the-polls-13092205|title=This Teen Activist Is Giving You One Good Reason Why You Should Get Out & Vote|last=Golden|first=Hannah|website=Elite Daily|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> The Future Coalition launched in September 2018 with the election campaign Walkout to Vote. Over 500 schools across the country walked out of class and marched to the polls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/377923-wisconsin-students-to-march-50-miles-to-ryans-hometown-to|title=Students to march 50 miles to Ryan's hometown to demand gun control|last=Savransky|first=Rebecca|date=2018-03-12|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowthisnews.com/https://nowthisnews.com/videos/politics/wisconsin-students-are-marching-to-paul-ryans-hometown|title=Wisconsin Students Are Marching To Paul Ryan's Hometown|last=nowthisnews|date=2018-03-29|website=NowThis|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards ==\n\n* Prudential Spirit of Community Award \u2013 National Honoree<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spirit.prudential.com/honoree/2018/wi/sarah-katie-eder|title=The Prudential Spirit Of Community Awards|website=spirit.prudential.com|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n* Diller Tikkun Olam Award<ref>{{